**Jonas Vingegaard Rasmussen** (; born 10 December 1996) is a Danish professional cyclist who rides for [WorldTeam](UCI)(UCI WorldTeam) . He won the [2022](2022 Tour de France) edition of the [de France](Tour)(Tour de France).

Vingegaard started as a youth rider for various Danish teams, making his breakthrough as a senior rider as part of [Continental](UCI)(UCI Continental Circuits) team [ColoQuick–Cult](Team ColoQuick) in 2016. He was known as a physical specimen and broke records in climbs, but still lacked major results on the road. As part of , which he joined in 2019,  he impressed at the [de Pologne](Tour)(2019 Tour de Pologne) and rode as a [domestique](domestique) for [Roglič](Primož)(Primož Roglič) at the [a España](Vuelta)(2020 Vuelta a España).

In April 2021, Vingegaard was named as a replacement for [Dumoulin](Tom)(Tom Dumoulin) in the team's [de France](Tour)(2021 Tour de France) squad. In the Tour, Vingegaard originally rode as a domestique for Roglič, who was one of the major favorites for the [classification](general)(General classification in the Tour de France). After Roglič crashed and later withdrew, Vingegaard took over as the team's only general classification contender. He gained international recognition after attacking on [Ventoux](Mont)(Mont Ventoux), dropping race leader and eventual winner [Pogačar](Tadej)(Tadej Pogačar) and finished second in the general classification.

In the [Tour de France](2022)(2022 Tour de France), Vingegaard was a favourite for the GC together with [Pogačar](Tadej)(Tadej Pogačar). Stage 11 included a final climb of the [du Granon](Col)(Col du Granon), a climb which had not been used since [1986](1986 Tour de France) where [LeMond](Greg)(Greg LeMond) seized the yellow jersey from [Hinault](Bernard)(Bernard Hinault). Vingegaard's Team Jumbo-Visma attacked Pogačar on the [du Télégraphe](Col)(Col du Télégraphe) and [du Galibier](Col)(Col du Galibier) with Roglič while having [Laporte](Christophe)(Christophe Laporte) and [Kruijswijk](Steven)(Steven Kruijswijk) nearby and [van Aert](Wout)(Wout van Aert) up the road. On the final climb Vingegaard attacked at the 5 km mark, and dropped Pogačar for the second time in his career, except this time Pogačar was not able to make it back. Relentlessly advancing, Vingegaard won the stage and the yellow jersey and gained +2:51 on Pogačar. This put Vingegaard in the lead and relegated Pogačar to third, behind second-placed [Bardet](Romain)(Romain Bardet). Vingegaard would not let go of the yellow jersey for the rest of the Tour, also dropping Pogačar on the final ascent on [Hautacam](Hautacam), after holding up a moment to wait for Pogačar to catch up after a fall in an act of [sportsmanship](sportsmanship). His efforts ultimately won him the 2022 Tour de France.
